{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_011zzWs74mSYLvUn4LwRecgh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Two issues:\n\n1. `TransactionSql<{}>` has no call signatures — the template literal syntax doesn't work on `TransactionSql`. I need to check how existing code uses the transaction handle. Looking at the migrate.ts code, it uses `tx.unsafe(...)`. But I need to use template literal syntax for parameterized queries. Let me check the postgres types more carefully.\n\nLooking at the postgres types:\n```\ninterface TransactionSql<TTypes extends Record<string, unknown> = {}> extends Omit<Sql<TTypes>, ...>\n```\n\nSo `TransactionSql` should have the same call signatures as `Sql`. \n\nBut TypeScript isn't recognizing those call signatures — this is likely because `Omit` doesn't preserve call signatures, which is a known TypeScript limitation. Looking at how the codebase actually handles this, I see transactions are only used in migrate.ts where they just call `tx.unsafe()`, so maybe I need to follow that pattern instead of trying to use template literals directly.\n\nI have a few options: use `tx.unsafe()` with parameterized queries, switch to the `postgres.Sql` type for less precision but better compatibility, or cast the transaction to include the call signature. Let me dig into the postgres type definitions to see what makes the most sense.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":740,"cache_read_input_tokens":46369,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":740},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f29ae509-f643-4ea1-906d-d19d18bc6bbf","uuid":"b57aa032-68d6-4eb2-a4e9-a5cd4f50b149"}
